[For background, in a prior ProMED-mail post, there was a letter to the editor from Skowronski DM, Janjua NZ, Kwindt TL, De Serres G in Eurosurveillance with a discussion on the unusual age distribution of the cases (see ProMED-mail Avian influenza, human (61): China H7N9 update 20130426.1674993, section [4] Immunological profiling):

"Perhaps the most intriguing impression to date from available surveillance findings has been the unexpected age/sex distribution of reported influenza A(H7N9) cases. The age range spans from 2 to 91 years, but 2/3 of influenza A(H7N9) cases have been 50 years of age or older and 2/3 have been male. Illness severity, with a substantial case fatality rate of 20 per cent, shows a similar age/sex profile. Unlike the pattern observed for influenza A(H5N1), children, both boys and girls and notably the school-aged, are under-represented among influenza A(H7N9) detections. Among the 1st 100 adult influenza A(H7N9) cases, men and women were equally represented in the youngest age category, 20-34 years, but men were 2-3-fold more frequent than women in older age groups. Furthermore, compared with women 20-34 years of age, women 50-64 and 65-79 years were each twice as frequent among influenza A(H7N9) detections. Conversely, men 50-64 and 65-79 years are each 4-5-fold more frequent among influenza A(H7N9) detections than men 20-34 years of age. While being careful not to over-interpret early surveillance data, what hypotheses might be invoked to explain that pattern?"

A few days later, there was another ProMED-mail post containing a line listing of the 1st 127 cases, providing information on age and sex of cases as well as dates of onset, death and geographic location of the cases. (While the data came from a FluTrackers report available at http://www.flutrackers.com/forum/showthread.php?p=489904, the information was extracted into the ProMED-mail post: Avian influenza, human (64): China H7N9 update 20130430.1680704).

ProMED-mail would like to thank Dr Fisman for his submission. Dr Fisman raises some interesting points above in his discussion. What awaits to be seen is results from serosurveys of the population in the affected areas for identification of prior exposure to the H7N9 by age and gender among the general population, and those who are in high risk professions/jobs that increase their probable exposure to these avian populations. - Mod.MPP]
